3) Composition & expression shifts and sample structure

2025-01-27

This script uses the R package cacoa (https://github.com/kharchenkolab/cacoa). In this script analysis of compositional changes and expression shifts as well as inspection of sample structure is performed.

Setup

#Load helper functions
source("/people/nrq364/NeuSiC/scRNA_helper_new.R")

library(cacoa)
library(magrittr)
library(dplyr)
library(conos)
library(pagoda2)
library(qs)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggrastr)

1. Read in data

Read in conos objet and annotation factor generated in notebook 2 clustering and annotation.

con <- qread("con.qs", nthreads = 10)
anno <- qread("anno.qs")

2. Generate cacoa object

condition <- setNames(c("control", "control", "control", "control","control", "control", "treated", "treated", "treated","treated", "treated", "treated"), names(con$samples))
cao <- Cacoa$new(con, cell.groups = anno, sample.groups=condition, n.cores = 10, ref.level = "control", target.level = "treated")

Plot UMAP using the cacoa object to check if data was loaded correctly.

cao$plotEmbedding(color.by='cell.groups', alpha=1, size=2, title='', 
                    plot.na=FALSE, show.legend=F, font.size=c(8,12), legend.position="bottom" )

qsave(cao, "cao.qs", nthreads = 10)

3. Compositional changes

Analyse which cell types change their abundance due to the treatment.

cao$estimateCellLoadings()

Plot compositional changes (this is just the default look of the plot, can be adjusted). Cell types above the red line are significantly altered. Negative cell loading means decreased abundance of the cell type in the treated samples, while positive cell loading points towards increased abundance in treated condition.

cao$plotCellLoadings(show.pvals = F)

4. Expression shifts

top.n.genes parameter needs to be adjusted per dataset. In case of neurons use a lower number than the default (1000) because neurons are very similar. If you normalize to among many similar genes, you will not get a meaningful result. Check sample positions in UMAP plot in expression.space (see 5.) when using different numbers of top.n.genes.

cao$estimateExpressionShiftMagnitudes(top.n.genes = 300)

Overall expression distance per condition.

cao$plotExpressionDistance(joint=TRUE, notch=TRUE, show.significance=TRUE )

Plot expression changes per cell type. y-axis shows magnitude of changes, while asterisks on top of bars show their significance. The more to the right the cell type is the more affected it is.

cao$plotExpressionShiftMagnitudes(show.pvalues = "adjusted")

5. Inspect sample structure

To inspect sample structure, expression shift and compositional analysis need to be run first. Create metadata table per sample.

metadata <- data.frame(row.names = levels(cao$sample.per.cell), condition=c("control", "control", "control", "control","control", "control", "treated", "treated", "treated","treated", "treated", "treated"),version =c("3.0", "3.0", "3.0","3.1","3.1","3.1","3.0", "3.0", "3.0","3.0","3.1","3.1"), sequencing= c("batch1", "batch1","batch2","batch3", "batch3","batch3","batch1", "batch1","batch2","batch2","batch3", "batch3"), sex = c("male","mix","male","mix", "mix","mix","mix","male" ,"mix", "mix","mix","mix") )
metadata

expression structure of samples

This function shows warning if metadata significantly affects results: This function only works in developer version, remotes::install_github(‘kharchenkolab/cacoa’, ref= “dev_k”)

pvals <- cao$estimateMetadataSeparation(sample.meta = metadata,  space = "expression.shifts")

Now we can show sample expression structure colored by one of the factors:

cao$plotSampleDistances(space='expression.shifts', font.size=4, show.sample.size=T, method="UMAP", sample.colors = setNames(metadata$sequencing, names(cao$sample.groups)), color.title = "sequencing") #change colour by specifying palette = ; method can be changed to "MDS"

compositional structure of samples

The same can be done for compostional structure of samples:

pvals <- cao$estimateMetadataSeparation(sample.meta = metadata,  space = "coda")
